Let's get back to your Arch/Hyprland setup. You’re looking for a Notification Daemon. Here are the two best options that fit your "dismiss quickly + history + scriptable" criteria perfectly.

1. Dunst (The Lightweight Classic)
Dunst is the "old reliable" of the Linux world. It’s highly customizable via a config file and extremely light on resources.

Dismissing: You can map mouse clicks or keyboard shortcuts to dismiss one or all notifications.

History: It has a "history" feature where you can tap a shortcut to bring back the last notification.

Scripting: It follows the Desktop Notifications Specification, so you use notify-send.

Installation: sudo pacman -S dunst libnotify

2. SwayNotificationCenter (The Modern Choice)
Since you’re on Hyprland, SwayNC is arguably the best fit. It feels native to Wayland and was built specifically for tiling window managers.

The "List" Feature: It includes a slide-out Control Center (like macOS or Windows) where all your old notifications sit until you clear them.

Dismissing: Very intuitive "X" buttons or swipe-to-dismiss functionality.

Waybar Integration: It has a dedicated Waybar module that shows a "Do Not Disturb" icon or a counter of missed notifications.

Scripting: Works with notify-send and has its own CLI (swaync-client) to toggle the panel.

Installation: yay -S swaynotificationcenter

How to trigger them from scripts
Both of these use libnotify, which provides the notify-send command. You can drop this into any bash script:

Bash
notify-send "System Update" "Your Arch build is finished." --icon=dialog-information --urgency=critical
